1
00:00:01,364 --> 00:00:20,536
foundation course one talk five the second noble truth the wheel of dependent origination there came a time in the buddha's life in late middle age when he decided to appoint one of his monks as a permanent attendant and he asked ananda a cousin to be that person

2
00:00:21,208 --> 00:00:31,504
Ananda agreed to do so, but only on condition that he could hear every word the Buddha spoke, and if he were to miss any talks, the Buddha would relate to him what he had said.

3
00:00:32,466 --> 00:00:33,186
The Buddha agreed.

4
00:00:34,829 --> 00:00:40,398
When the Buddha died, a great council was held to bring together all the discourses and make a compilation.

5
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:45,845
It was this very same Ananda who came to be relied upon to supply the discourses.

6
00:00:47,027 --> 00:00:49,832
He seems to have had quite a phenomenal audio memory.

7
00:00:50,453 --> 00:00:58,774
lucky in an oral tradition, which was to hand down these discourses by rote learning for 500 years, before they were finally committed to paper.

8
00:01:00,277 --> 00:01:07,736
So it is that all the discourses are prefaced, Thus have I heard, and then there follows the place and occasion for the discourse.

9
00:01:10,736 --> 00:01:22,850
On this particular occasion, it is this same Ananda who tells the Buddha that although the teaching on the wheel of dependent origination is deep and profound, yet he, Ananda, found it to be self-evident and fathomable.

10
00:01:23,951 --> 00:01:25,112
The Buddha rebukes him.

11
00:01:25,653 --> 00:01:27,316
Don't say that, Ananda, don't say it.

12
00:01:27,816 --> 00:01:35,444
This teaching of mine, the wheel of dependent origination, is not only profound and deep, it also bears the signs of being so.

13
00:01:36,640 --> 00:01:42,010
Then the Buddha goes on to say that it is because people have not grasped this that their lives continue to be miserable.

14
00:01:44,635 --> 00:01:49,222
In a way, the teaching on the Wheel of Dependent Origination is the centrepiece of the Buddha's doctrine.

15
00:01:50,064 --> 00:01:55,013
It encapsulates not only the Four Noble Truths, but the whole of Buddhist psychology.

16
00:01:55,974 --> 00:02:00,082
It is an explanation of how we come to suffer and why we do so.

17
00:02:00,501 --> 00:02:01,927
It describes this in detail.

18
00:02:02,750 --> 00:02:11,001
Of late, there was a renowned teacher in Burma, the Mogok Theodore, believed to be an Arahant, a Buddhist saint, who taught everything through this doctrine.

19
00:02:13,495 --> 00:02:30,522
Although the formulation of the Four Noble Truths came first during the reflections after the Enlightenment, it is said that after a period of seven days following the Enlightenment, the whole formula of the wheel came to the Buddha as he emerged from concentration in the early night, and that later he understood it in reverse order.

20
00:02:32,145 --> 00:02:35,031
Here we can only hope to get a general idea of this teaching.

21
00:02:35,229 --> 00:02:42,206
We shall look at it as a day-to-day psychology and how it helps us to understand the meditation we do and how it can help us in daily life.

22
00:02:42,989 --> 00:02:46,316
For the Buddha's teaching is not some empty descriptive philosophy.

23
00:02:46,957 --> 00:02:51,990
It's a theory we must prove to be true for ourselves by putting it into practice, by trying it out.

24
00:02:54,518 --> 00:03:05,891
The first link, which is not to be considered a first cause, but an underlying precondition, out of which all our suffering, and indeed our existence arises, is ignorance.

25
00:03:07,234 --> 00:03:13,381
Ignorance here means not knowing, just as I might not know your name simply because I've not heard it.

26
00:03:14,703 --> 00:03:18,967
This not knowing produces wrong understanding about life, delusions in fact.

27
00:03:19,628 --> 00:03:22,331
These delusions are inbuilt in our psychology.

28
00:03:22,548 --> 00:03:29,497
These delusions cause us to make decisions and act in certain ways which are unskillful and bring about unwholesome results.

29
00:03:32,600 --> 00:03:35,003
It is in this way that mind is conditioned.

30
00:03:35,805 --> 00:03:41,853
Our mental life, our psychology, is full of habits which have been produced by our own decision-making, our wills.

31
00:03:42,774 --> 00:03:51,846
However, because our wills have acted upon wrong information, those delusions of ours, so the mind ends up with unskillful or unwholesome conditions.

32
00:03:52,213 --> 00:03:54,455
which in turn causes further suffering.

33
00:03:56,578 --> 00:04:02,283
When I am a child, because I don't know any better, because I am ignorant, I accept what is given to me.

34
00:04:03,425 --> 00:04:09,031
If, for instance, I am told that people of other religions are evil, and to be avoided, at first I believe it.

35
00:04:10,132 --> 00:04:17,699
This wrong understanding now produces an attitude, which in turn produces words and actions of particular behaviour whenever I should meet such people.

36
00:04:19,201 --> 00:04:21,343
I have internalised my parents' prejudice.

37
00:04:22,201 --> 00:04:23,985
An interesting word, prejudge.

38
00:04:24,947 --> 00:04:27,531
To form an opinion about something before the facts are known.

39
00:04:28,875 --> 00:04:31,100
Deluded by this prejudice, I'm on my guard.

40
00:04:31,160 --> 00:04:31,841
I feel fear.

41
00:04:32,322 --> 00:04:33,245
These people are evil.

42
00:04:33,644 --> 00:04:35,288
I must get away before they do me harm.

43
00:04:35,709 --> 00:04:38,175
Or worse, if only we could be rid of them.

44
00:04:39,879 --> 00:04:41,862
Upon these thoughts, I avoid them.

45
00:04:42,062 --> 00:04:52,658
The important point to understand here is that although I have received a prejudice from my parents, and although I have been taught an attitude in the final analysis, I make the decision to act upon it.

46
00:04:53,579 --> 00:04:58,447
In this way, I reinforce it so that it now becomes my prejudice.

47
00:04:59,870 --> 00:05:09,824
All these decisions, acts of will, build up in the child's mind until the way I behave with people of other religions will be simply a blind conditional response.

48
00:05:10,192 --> 00:05:12,677
I may even have forgotten the reasons why I behave like that.

49
00:05:13,117 --> 00:05:21,690
In fact, to the child become an adult, such behaviour comes to be accepted as perfectly proper and self-evidently righteous.

50
00:05:23,795 --> 00:05:32,809
So if we take any point of our lives, say when we wake up, we bring with us from the past all our ignorance and our delusive conditionings, the mental habits we've developed.

51
00:05:34,543 --> 00:05:39,911
Upon this twin base of ignorance and conditioned mental states, we perform all our activities.

52
00:05:40,814 --> 00:05:44,119
As soon as we wake, the next five links on the wheel come into being.

53
00:05:44,538 --> 00:05:48,504
The first is consciousness itself, just that faculty in the mind that knows.

54
00:05:49,547 --> 00:05:58,019
With this arises all the rest of the mind, the mental aggregates of sensations, perceptions, and volitional conditionings, and at the same time, the body itself.

55
00:05:59,165 --> 00:06:02,108
Because of this mind and body, the six senses are activated.

56
00:06:02,730 --> 00:06:08,778
The sixth sense being the mind itself as a sense base receiving information from the other five senses.

57
00:06:10,300 --> 00:06:13,363
Because of these senses, contact is made with the world out there.

58
00:06:14,365 --> 00:06:19,872
When this contact is made, feelings arise we experience as pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

59
00:06:21,035 --> 00:06:33,110
Here then is the human being as a receiver of information, the consciousness, the mental faculties and the body, the sense bases, contact with the world through these senses, and feelings caused by these contacts.

60
00:06:36,535 --> 00:06:40,841
Again, it is important to remember that everything has arisen because of something else.

61
00:06:41,581 --> 00:06:45,286
The human being comes into life at every moment of life in this way.

62
00:06:45,773 --> 00:06:52,942
Even in deep sleep there is some form of consciousness and sense contact, or how else could we pull a blanket over us when cold?

63
00:06:54,464 --> 00:07:01,716
This moment is a product of all the past and contains in it the effects of all our yesterday's decisions, skillful and unskillful.

64
00:07:02,976 --> 00:07:08,305
Some are realized, others lie potential in that moment, to be realized at some future time.

65
00:07:10,192 --> 00:07:17,060
To look at it another way, as soon as I see an apple, the first light that strikes the retina, the sense base, is the contact.

66
00:07:17,600 --> 00:07:20,964
Upon the contact feeling arises, I know this feeling, I am conscious of it.

67
00:07:22,226 --> 00:07:25,029
All this has happened by way of the physical and mental properties.

68
00:07:25,370 --> 00:07:31,778
In other words, the whole process is dependent, one thing on another, hence the wheel of dependent origination.

69
00:07:32,887 --> 00:07:41,300
Perhaps it would be better called interdependent origination since all these functions, properties, interrelate and work one upon the other.

70
00:07:43,021 --> 00:07:44,985
However, this is not the end of the story.

71
00:07:45,345 --> 00:07:46,307
There are yet more links.

72
00:07:47,487 --> 00:07:54,096
In the previous five links, ignorance has been the latent factor affecting all our perception of things the way we understand.

73
00:07:55,019 --> 00:07:59,605
It is the next link where the ignorance factor comes again more obviously into play.

74
00:08:00,766 --> 00:08:06,593
As soon as pleasurable feelings are experienced, because of our past deluded conditioning, desire for them arises.

75
00:08:07,634 --> 00:08:14,903
As soon as desire has arisen, there is a strengthening of it, if the wheel is to progress onto craving, grasping, even obsession.

76
00:08:16,045 --> 00:08:22,153
Once this has happened, the will comes into play, and the desire is realized, activated, satisfied.

77
00:08:24,276 --> 00:08:30,603
If we return to my apple, as soon as I saw the apple, there arose in me pleasurable feelings conditioned by past apple-eating.

78
00:08:31,192 --> 00:08:36,938
As soon as this happened, desire for more of those pleasurable feelings, not the apple itself, notice, arose in me.

79
00:08:38,100 --> 00:08:41,604
This desire takes hold of my mind in the form of grasping and craving.

80
00:08:42,284 --> 00:08:44,648
Before I know it, I've made the decision to eat it.

81
00:08:45,568 --> 00:08:48,772
When I actually eat the apple, I become the eater of the apple.

82
00:08:49,592 --> 00:08:53,437
I become absorbed in it, lost in it, totally self-identified with it.

83
00:08:54,139 --> 00:08:55,360
This is becoming.

84
00:08:55,778 --> 00:08:57,559
This is what Buddhism means by karma.

85
00:08:58,080 --> 00:09:05,248
Karma is simply becoming, being my actions, whether verbal or physical, and it is all brought about through my own will.

86
00:09:07,509 --> 00:09:08,730
What about aversion and hatred?

87
00:09:09,432 --> 00:09:11,774
Here, it is simply seen as a type of desire.

88
00:09:12,434 --> 00:09:19,361
If, for instance, I don't like apples, my conditioned response may be to ignore it, that is, not wanting, not wishing to see it.

89
00:09:20,523 --> 00:09:23,245
If I had a disgust for it, I might throw it away in the bin.

90
00:09:23,846 --> 00:09:25,227
My desire is to remove it,

91
00:09:26,659 --> 00:09:29,102
Aversion and hatred are simply the obverse of desire.

92
00:09:29,503 --> 00:09:30,985
I want it, I don't want it.

93
00:09:31,304 --> 00:09:31,865
It's all want.

94
00:09:32,346 --> 00:09:33,467
It's all a matter of desire.

95
00:09:34,528 --> 00:09:38,013
Fear is also desire, in this case, the desire to remove myself.

96
00:09:39,073 --> 00:09:42,817
If I had a phobia of apples, I might shrink away when I see one or run off.

97
00:09:44,139 --> 00:09:49,304
If they are neutral feelings, we usually remain ignorant of them, such as the sensations of our breathing process.

98
00:09:50,386 --> 00:09:53,409
Here, I'm using the word sensations and feelings to mean the same thing.

99
00:09:54,048 --> 00:10:03,039
What separates them into pleasant, unpleasant and neutral is our perception of them, how we name or label these sensations through our past experience.

100
00:10:05,342 --> 00:10:06,985
The wheel has not yet finished turning.

101
00:10:08,427 --> 00:10:16,398
Having made visual contact with the apple, felt all the attendant sensations of delight, and knowing this, having reacted with desire and craving, I eat it.

102
00:10:17,399 --> 00:10:18,301
Now, of course, I've finished.

103
00:10:18,821 --> 00:10:19,562
I've eaten the apple.

104
00:10:20,283 --> 00:10:23,126
It took a little time, but I saw the apple coming to an end.

105
00:10:23,308 --> 00:10:28,553
my sensual pleasure coming to an end, suddenly I'm left with just a core and a few pips.

106
00:10:29,034 --> 00:10:32,278
The apple is no more, and my delight is gone.

107
00:10:33,558 --> 00:10:35,721
These are the last two links.

108
00:10:35,740 --> 00:10:39,083
Having decided to do something, I am born into that action.

109
00:10:39,664 --> 00:10:42,086
This birth is the becoming, is the karma.

110
00:10:42,927 --> 00:10:46,130
It is in this way that we are reborn from moment to moment.

111
00:10:47,131 --> 00:10:51,155
But as soon as I am born, born again, reborn into something,

112
00:10:51,658 --> 00:10:58,948
that thing must come by way of a decaying or a declining process to an end, at some time or other.

113
00:10:59,951 --> 00:11:01,894
Everything decays and dies.

114
00:11:03,274 --> 00:11:10,065
However, in the process, I have also reinforced my conditioning, those volitional conditionings that sit as potential in my mind.

115
00:11:11,167 --> 00:11:18,476
I shall react very much the same when I next aspire an apple, and the wheel of dependent origination will turn yet again.

116
00:11:21,072 --> 00:11:24,258
This is an explanation of the whole of moral human behavior.

117
00:11:25,399 --> 00:11:40,988
Although this is a harmless example of apple eating, it's the same psychology that produces negative habits of smoking, alcoholism, sexual deviancy, crimes of violence, murder, and the same that causes selfishness and egotism to enter into the acts of love and compassion.

118
00:11:42,267 --> 00:11:53,200
If a young teenage boy continually bombarded with sexual images uses the medium of sex to develop feelings of hate and the pleasures of cruelty, is it any wonder that sooner or later there's a rape?

119
00:11:54,182 --> 00:12:00,909
Indeed, this wheel can be formulated in a slightly different way that brings this personality development more into relief.

120
00:12:03,212 --> 00:12:07,717
It is taught in Buddhism that upon the arising of a thought, there is an action.

121
00:12:08,710 --> 00:12:17,503
A thought here includes all the underlying ignorant delusion, the basic human faculties of body and mind needed to bring this about, and the deluded desires.

122
00:12:18,344 --> 00:12:21,589
Action is that point of decision which is an act of will.

123
00:12:22,910 --> 00:12:25,335
Upon a set of actions, a habit is established.

124
00:12:26,255 --> 00:12:31,003
So we see that if we turn the wheel in a certain direction often enough, it will keep turning that way.

125
00:12:31,423 --> 00:12:32,985
It gathers momentum.

126
00:12:33,005 --> 00:12:34,087
Habits are hard to break.

127
00:12:34,609 --> 00:12:36,912
Long-established habits, harder still.

128
00:12:38,495 --> 00:12:40,577
Now a collection of habits is a personality.

129
00:12:41,379 --> 00:12:42,961
That's worth pondering on.

130
00:12:42,981 --> 00:12:46,827
A personality in Buddhism is just a whole collection of conditioned responses.

131
00:12:47,928 --> 00:12:50,091
This is not to say that humans are automatons.

132
00:12:50,974 --> 00:12:52,635
For remember, we condition ourselves.

133
00:12:53,717 --> 00:12:58,284
It's when we don't know this or forget this that we lose the ability to direct our lives.

134
00:12:59,486 --> 00:13:03,011
And so it is that this personality determines our destiny.

135
00:13:04,653 --> 00:13:07,118
How important it is to become aware of our thoughts.

136
00:13:07,840 --> 00:13:14,427
If you were to say to an ordinary person in the street, was worse the thought of murder, the threatening of murder, or the action of murder?

137
00:13:15,408 --> 00:13:20,413
The answer would be the action itself, since up to that time no actual harm had been done.

138
00:13:21,695 --> 00:13:24,918
And indeed, from the victim's and society's point of view, this is quite right.

139
00:13:25,740 --> 00:13:30,865
But from a mental process point of view and the murderer's point of view, the most important was the thought.

140
00:13:31,466 --> 00:13:35,129
For without the thought, the action would never have arisen, nor indeed the threatening.

141
00:13:36,476 --> 00:13:46,591
From our point of view as meditators, this is something we have to grasp very deeply indeed, if we're eventually to escape this wheel of dependent origination, this wheel of suffering.

142
00:13:49,317 --> 00:13:54,764
In longer periods of meditation practice, such as a weekend or a week-long course, this process becomes more obvious to us.

143
00:13:55,546 --> 00:14:04,779
And with the practice of moment-to-moment awareness in our daily life, we can begin to catch this process and see how it's doing us harm, and more important, see how we can stop it.

144
00:14:07,678 --> 00:14:09,061
So how do we undermine this wheel?

145
00:14:09,902 --> 00:14:20,615
First of all, we have to accept that all the links up to feeling, that is, all the ignorance, volitional conditionings, consciousness, mind and body, the six senses, contact, and the feelings that arise, are a given.

146
00:14:21,196 --> 00:14:21,897
They are conditioned.

147
00:14:22,477 --> 00:14:25,461
We can do nothing about those thoughts arising in the mind.

148
00:14:25,922 --> 00:14:26,883
They will come of their own.

149
00:14:28,184 --> 00:14:33,871
Let me return to the problem of religious prejudice, which, sad to say, is very much a world phenomenon.

150
00:14:35,505 --> 00:14:43,179
Now because of this conditioning, when I come to know a person who is of a different religion to me, unpleasant, perhaps hateful thoughts and feelings arise.

151
00:14:43,922 --> 00:14:49,412
This is my conditioning, prejudicial, caused by a combination of my upbringing and my own past acts of will.

152
00:14:50,394 --> 00:14:53,779
It's a combination of my believing, misinformation and acting upon it.

153
00:14:54,682 --> 00:14:58,729
But at this moment, when I see this other person, there is no act of will.

154
00:14:58,708 --> 00:15:00,910
I am not actively prejudicial.

155
00:15:01,652 --> 00:15:04,014
Upon the seeing there arises a conditioned response.

156
00:15:04,375 --> 00:15:07,839
There is nothing in the world I can do to stop that arising.

157
00:15:09,400 --> 00:15:14,166
It is in the next links that this conditioned prejudice, already arisen in my mind, is acted upon.

158
00:15:15,246 --> 00:15:28,682
It is at the actual point of reaction, the desire, the craving and the action or becoming, where the choice arises to develop, reinforce these prejudicial conditionings or to let them go, to just observe them.

159
00:15:29,842 --> 00:15:34,630
If I decide to act upon them, to obey their suggestions, then I will strengthen my religious prejudice.

160
00:15:35,672 --> 00:15:36,813
I will feed it, develop it.

161
00:15:37,836 --> 00:15:44,285
But if I refuse to do so, if I just observe them, let them go, fail to obey them, I undermine that conditioning.

162
00:15:45,107 --> 00:15:51,597
For that conditioning needs my continued, active, willful support to grow, to develop, to sustain.

163
00:15:52,067 --> 00:15:59,755
More, in deciding and willing not to act upon their suggestions, I set up a more wholesome conditioning of positive values.

164
00:16:00,636 --> 00:16:08,926
I am creating a new response, a new conditioning, which not only counteracts and undermines the old negative one, but is also producing something new.

165
00:16:10,346 --> 00:16:14,611
In short, initial thoughts and feelings are products of past action and conditioning.

166
00:16:15,232 --> 00:16:17,534
It is what I do with them that matters.

167
00:16:20,249 --> 00:16:23,394
Now you will have noticed that I've used the concepts of wholesome and unwholesome.

168
00:16:23,953 --> 00:16:25,576
Indeed, this is Buddhist training.

169
00:16:26,057 --> 00:16:33,207
It is to begin to recognize what is unwholesome, harmful for ourselves and other beings, and to refuse to develop any further those very conditionings.

170
00:16:34,208 --> 00:16:40,337
Secondly, it is to foster within ourselves and to develop thoughts and feelings that are beneficial, wholesome.

171
00:16:41,119 --> 00:16:42,581
In this way we purify the mind.

172
00:16:42,961 --> 00:16:46,307
In this way we are slowing down, wearing out the wheels.

173
00:16:48,768 --> 00:16:57,332
So long as we react to and indulge in unwholesome states of mind, so long are we deepening our ignorance and so worsening our suffering.

174
00:16:57,352 --> 00:17:03,250
When we begin to let go of unwholesome states of mind and develop wholesome states of mind, we rid ourselves of ignorance.

175
00:17:04,343 --> 00:17:19,210
As we begin to rid ourselves of ignorance, the mind, clear of its obscuring wrong attitudes, opinions and prejudices, becomes more and more insightful until it can begin to plumb the depths of our being and see what it is we really are.

176
00:17:20,112 --> 00:17:25,862
This seeing ourselves as we really are, beyond greed, hatred and delusion, is the nirvanic experience.

177
00:17:27,461 --> 00:17:37,251
Every time we undermine an unwholesome conditioning, we come to understand more deeply the insights the Buddha had on the night when he discovered the wheel of dependent origination in its reverse order.

178
00:17:38,192 --> 00:17:46,039
Indeed, as ignorance is destroyed, so are all the links on the chain, one upon the other, and with it goes our suffering.

179
00:17:47,161 --> 00:17:48,301
This doesn't mean annihilation.

180
00:17:48,803 --> 00:17:54,127
The Buddha continued to live another 45 years after his enlightenment, but in perfect peace and joy.

181
00:17:54,563 --> 00:18:02,531
When he was asked what happened to a Buddha, or a totally purified one upon death, his answer was that it was simply ineffable, not describable.

182
00:18:03,373 --> 00:18:08,258
Parinibbana is beyond the wheel of becoming, the wheel of dependent origination.

183
00:18:10,500 --> 00:18:15,665
So this is our task, to recognize unwholesome conditioning, thoughts and feelings for what they are.

184
00:18:16,386 --> 00:18:16,906
Let them go.

185
00:18:18,087 --> 00:18:21,231
We have to train ourselves in more wholesome ways of thinking and feeling.

186
00:18:22,113 --> 00:18:23,253
We can do this.

187
00:18:23,707 --> 00:18:24,988
This is our freedom.

188
00:18:26,028 --> 00:18:29,752
We have the power, through our own wills, to change our states of mind.

189
00:18:30,874 --> 00:18:37,340
In meditation we see these conditioning, these states of mind, these emotions and moods, just as passing things, transient phenomena.

190
00:18:38,201 --> 00:18:39,823
We mustn't attach to them.

191
00:18:39,843 --> 00:18:41,484
We mustn't identify with them.

192
00:18:42,385 --> 00:18:45,890
And so too in daily life, while going about our day-to-day activities.

193
00:18:47,250 --> 00:18:50,835
In this way our lives will become happier, more peaceful.

194
00:18:51,895 --> 00:18:53,156
When all conditions ripen,

195
00:18:53,338 --> 00:18:59,009
wholesome conditions, insight will arise naturally into that state beyond change.

196
00:19:00,029 --> 00:19:01,894
Nibbana is assured.

197
00:19:03,936 --> 00:19:06,682
